    <text>
        <body>
           <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" resp="#POC">
            <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><persName><name>ᚌ<supplied reason="lost">ᚓ</supplied>ᚂ<unclear reason="damage">ᚐ</unclear>ᚌᚅ<supplied reason="lost">ᚔ</supplied></name> <w type="formula" lemma="avias"><supplied reason="lost">ᚐ</supplied>ᚃ<supplied reason="lost">ᚔ</supplied></w> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="stroke"/></persName>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" resp="#POC">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><persName><name>G<supplied reason="lost">E</supplied>L<unclear reason="damage">A</unclear>GN<supplied reason="lost">I</supplied></name> <w type="formula" lemma="avias"><supplied reason="lost">A</supplied>V<supplied reason="lost">I</supplied></w> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="stroke"/></persName>
                </ab>
                <ab type="list">G[E]LAGN[I A]V[I ---̣]</ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <app n="1">
                    <note>The inscription appears to begin with a G, followed by a damaged section which could have held 5, or more likely, 4 vowel strokes (E?), than an L followed by a damaged vowel stroke (A), then G and N followed by 5 or 6 damaged vowel strokes. Finally, there is a V and 2 vowel strokes running up to the broken corner of the stone. The remainder of the inscription cannot be read as it is on an edge of the stone that is hidden by the wall.</note>
                </app>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>'of Gelán grandson of..?'</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>As Manning and Moore (1997, 372) suggest regarding GELAGNI, <q>if a long é was intended (Gellagni) would be cognate with Old Irish <persName xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/25799">Gíallán</ref></persName>, related to <distinct xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/25788">gíall</ref></distinct> `a hostage'. If a short e was intended (Gelagni), it would be cognate with Old Irish *<distinct xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/25570">Gelán</ref></distinct>, related to <distinct xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/25565">gel</ref></distinct> 'bright'</q>. The former is actually attested as a personal name in the <title type="book">Félire Óengusso</title>. AVI is a common formula word found in the ogham corpus, from Old Irish <distinct xml:lang="sga"><ref target="dil.ie/42573">úa</ref></distinct> 'grandson, descendant'</p>
            </div>
            <div type="bibliography">
                <listBibl>
                    <bibl><ptr target="MAN1997"/>
                    <citedRange>370-372</citedRange>
                    </bibl>
                 </listBibl>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
